Searchlight, Nevada

Searchlight is an [unincorporated town](/Unincorporated_towns_in_Nevada) and a [census-designated place](/Census-designated_place) (CDP) situated in [Clark County, Nevada](/Clark_County,_Nevada), United States. It occupies a topographical saddle, nestled between two distinct mountain ranges. The most recent [census](/Census) in 2020 recorded a population of 445 individuals within the CDP.

## History

The origins of Searchlight's name are shrouded in the kind of folklore that clings to old mining towns like dust to a forgotten shaft. According to the late [U.S. Senator](/United_States_Senate) [Harry Reid](/Harry_Reid), who knew the area intimately, the prevailing story attributes the moniker to prospector George Frederick Colton. On May 6, 1897, while searching for [gold](/Gold) in the unforgiving terrain, Colton is said to have remarked that it would take a [searchlight](/Searchlight) to find any significant ore deposits. Fate, it seems, had a sense of humor, for shortly thereafter, he struck gold. This discovery ignited a boom era, a period when Searchlight actually boasted a larger population than its now-famous neighbor, [Las Vegas](/Las_Vegas). During this heady time, Searchlight was part of [Lincoln County, Nevada](/Lincoln_County,_Nevada). As discussions began to coalesce around the idea of carving [Clark County, Nevada](/Clark_County,_Nevada) out of Lincoln County, Searchlight was even considered as a potential county seat. Between 1907 and 1910, the mines here yielded an impressive $7 million in gold and other precious minerals, sustaining a population of approximately 1,500 souls. The valuable ore was transported to [Barnwell](/Barnwell,_California) via the specialized [Barnwell and Searchlight Railway](/Barnwell_and_Searchlight_Railway).

Reid, however, was known to be a meticulous chronicler of his hometown's history and often debunked less substantiated tales. One such fanciful story suggested Colton was lighting a Searchlight brand [match](/Match) when he made his pivotal discovery. Reid, ever the pragmatist, dismissed this, noting that the Searchlight matches weren't even available until 1898, a year *after* the discovery. Another persistent narrative claims Colton believed the elevated location was advantageous, hence the name. His mine itself was reportedly named the [Duplex](/Duplex_(building)) due to the ore being found on two distinct levels.

The fortunes of Searchlight waned considerably after 1917. It persisted, however, as a stop along the [Arrowhead Highway](/Arrowhead_Trail_(auto_trail)). The landscape shifted again in 1927 when [U.S. Route 91](/U.S._Route_91) was rerouted, bypassing the town and contributing to a drastic population decline to a mere 50 residents.

A flicker of resurgence occurred in the 1930s and 1940s, fueled by the monumental construction of the nearby [Hoover Dam](/Hoover_Dam). During this period, the town also hosted the El Rey Bordello, a notorious establishment that operated until it was consumed by fire in the early 1950s. The last gold mine in the area finally ceased operations around 1953, marking the end of an era.

## Geography

Searchlight is characterized by its [desert climate](/Desert_climate), classified under the [Köppen climate classification](/K%C3%B6ppen_climate_classification) as BWh. This means it experiences scorching summers and mild, cool winters, though sub-freezing temperatures are not entirely unheard of. The town's elevation, sitting at 3,547 feet (1,081 meters), provides a slight reprieve from the extreme heat found in lower-lying Mojave Desert locales like [Baker, California](/Baker,_California), [Needles, California](/Needles,_California), and [Fort Mohave, Arizona](/Fort_Mohave,_Arizona). Nevertheless, summer days can still be brutally hot. The arid environment and altitude mean that temperatures tend to plummet rapidly after sunset, particularly during the warmer months. Winter days are generally pleasant, with highs well above freezing, and the mercury dips below freezing only on a handful of nights each year. The [diurnal temperature variation](/Diurnal_temperature_variation) is a significant feature of its climate.

