### 2000 Census

At the time of the 2000 census, Searchlight CDP reported a population of 576 individuals. This comprised 315 households and 136 families. The population density stood at 44.1 people per square mile (17.0 per square kilometer), with 444 housing units spread across the area, resulting in an average density of 34.0 units per square mile (13.1 per square kilometer).

The racial composition of Searchlight was predominantly [White](/White_(U.S._Census)), accounting for 95.0% of the population. Smaller percentages were identified as [African American](/African_American_(U.S._Census)) (0.7%), [Native American](/Native_American_(U.S._Census)) (0.7%), [Asian](/Asian_(U.S._Census)) (0.2%), and [Pacific Islander](/Pacific_Islander_(U.S._Census)) (0.2%). An additional 1.7% identified with [other races](/Race_(United_States_Census)), and 1.6% identified with two or more races. The [Hispanic](/Hispanic_(U.S._Census)) or [Latino](/Latino_(U.S._Census)) population, regardless of race, constituted 3.7% of the residents.

Of the 315 households, 8.6% included children under the age of 18. A significant portion, 34.9%, consisted of [married couples](/Marriage) living together. Female householders with no husband present accounted for 5.1% of households, while 56.8% were classified as non-families. Nearly half of all households (48.3%) were composed of single individuals, and a substantial 23.5% comprised individuals aged 65 or older living alone. The average household size was 1.76 people, and the average family size was 2.46.

The age distribution showed 10.1% of the population under 18, 3.1% between 18 and 24, 20.0% from 25 to 44, 35.8% from 45 to 64, and 31.1% aged 65 and older. The median age in Searchlight was 55 years. The gender distribution revealed a notable imbalance, with 125.9 males for every 100 females. This disparity was even more pronounced in the adult population, with 131.3 males for every 100 females aged 18 and over.

The [median household income](/Median_household_income) in 2000 was $24,407, with the median family income at $29,323. Males earned a median income of $26,563, while females earned $27,868. The [per capita income](/Per_capita_income) for the CDP was $19,606. Worryingly, none of the families in Searchlight were living below the [poverty line](/Poverty_line), yet 14.6% of the total population fell into this category, including no individuals under 18 or over 64.

## Education

Primary and secondary public education for Searchlight residents is managed by the [Clark County School District](/Clark_County_School_District). The district operates Reid Elementary School, serving students from Kindergarten to 5th grade, directly within Searchlight.

Furthermore, Searchlight is served by a branch of the Las Vegas-Clark County Library District, providing public library services to the community.

## Transportation

### Public Transport

The [Silver Rider Transit](/Silver_Rider_Transit) system offers express bus services connecting Searchlight with [Laughlin](/Laughlin,_Nevada) and [Las Vegas](/Las_Vegas). For travel to [Harry Reid International Airport](/Harry_Reid_International_Airport) in Las Vegas, private shuttle companies provide transportation options.

### Highways

Searchlight's strategic location is marked by its position at the intersection of two significant highways. [U.S. Route 95](/U.S._Route_95_in_Nevada) runs north towards [Boulder City](/Boulder_City,_Nevada) and the greater [Las Vegas Valley](/Las_Vegas_Valley), and south towards [Needles, California](/Needles,_California). Additionally, [Nevada State Route 164](/Nevada_State_Route_164) originates in Searchlight, heading west towards the California border, where it transitions into Nipton Road and eventually connects to [Interstate 15](/Interstate_15).

## Notable People

*   **Rex Bell**: A prominent figure in [westerns](/Western_(genre)) films and a politician, Rex Bell, along with his wife, the silent film star [Clara Bow](/Clara_Bow), owned the [Walking Box Ranch](/Walking_Box_Ranch) near Searchlight. The ranch was a popular haunt for many Hollywood luminaries.
*   **Edith Head**: A legendary costume designer, Edith Head holds the record for the most Academy Awards won by a woman. She spent part of her formative years in the mining town of Searchlight.
*   **William Harrell Nellis**: An aviator whose bravery and skill earned him posthumous recognition, William Harrell Nellis is the namesake of the renowned [Nellis Air Force Base](/Nellis_Air_Force_Base).
*   **Harry Reid**: A towering figure in American politics, Harry Reid served as a United States Senator from 1987 to 2017, holding the position of Senate Majority Leader from 2007 to 2015. His roots are deeply embedded in Searchlight, where he was born. Reid's autobiography details a childhood in a modest shack, with a father who worked the mines and a mother who worked in the town's brothels. His early life was marked by hardship, including his father's suicide and a long commute to high school.

## In Popular Culture

*   In 1907, the spirited piano piece known as the "[Searchlight Rag](/Searchlight_Rag)" was published, composed by the legendary [Scott Joplin](/Scott_Joplin). The inspiration for its title reportedly stemmed from the experiences of Joplin's friends, the Turpin brothers, who had prospected in the Searchlight area in the early 1890s. Their vivid tales, recounted to patrons of their bar, ultimately led to the rag's distinctive name.
*   Searchlight features prominently as a location within the popular video game [Fallout: New Vegas](/Fallout_New_Vegas). In the game's post-apocalyptic narrative, it is depicted as an outpost that has succumbed to the ravages of nuclear war, becoming irradiated.

